[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:storybook/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:storybook/essentials] Storybook essentials is a set of tools that help you build, test, and document your components within Storybook.
[src:storybook/essentials] It comes with a recommended configuration out of the box.
[src:storybook/essentials] Many of the features above can be configured via parameters.
[src:storybook/essentials] See each feature's documentation (linked above) for more details.
[src:storybook/essentials] If you need to disable any of the essential features, you can do it by changing your `.storybook/main.js|ts` file.
[src:storybook/essentials] You can use the following keys for each individual feature: `actions`, `backgrounds`, `controls`, `highlight`, `measure`, `outline`, `toolbars`, and `viewport`.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] JavaScript frameworks are an essential part of modern front-end web development, providing developers with tried and tested tools for building scalable, interactive web applications.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] Many modern companies use frameworks as a standard part of their tooling, so many front-end development jobs now require framework experience.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] This set of articles provides a comfortable starting point to help you begin learning frameworks.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] We are not aiming to exhaustively teach you everything you need to know about React/ReactDOM, or Vue, or some other specific framework; the framework teams' own docs (and other resources) do that job already.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] After that, we'll provide some tutorials covering the essentials React, a popular framework choice, to provide you with enough context and familiarity to start going into greater depth yourself.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] We want you to go forward and learn about frameworks in a pragmatic way that doesn't forget about web platform fundamental best practices such as accessibility.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] We also provide some tutorials covering the basics of other framework choices, for those who want to make a different choice to React.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] You should really learn the basics of the core web languages first before attempting to move on to learning client-side frameworks — HTML, CSS, and especially JavaScript.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] Your code will be richer and more professional as a result, and you'll be able to troubleshoot problems with more confidence if you understand the fundamental web platform features that the frameworks are building on top of.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] We begin our look at frameworks with a general overview of the area, looking at a brief history of JavaScript and frameworks, why frameworks exist and what they give us, how to start thinking about choosing a framework to learn, and what alternatives there are to client-side frameworks.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] Each major JavaScript framework has a different approach to updating the DOM, handling browser events, and providing an enjoyable developer experience.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] This article will explore the main features of "the big 4" frameworks, looking at how frameworks tend to work from a high level and the differences between them.
