[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] We want to say this upfront — we've **not** chosen the frameworks we are focusing on because we think they are the best, or because we endorse them in any way.
[src:storybook/frameworks-libraries] We just think they score highly on the above criteria.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] A **JavaScript library** is a library of pre-written JavaScript code that allows for easier development of JavaScript-based applications, especially for AJAX and other web-centric technologies.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] They can be included in a website by embedding it directly in the HTML via a script tag.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] With the expanded demands for JavaScript, an easier means for programmers to develop such dynamic interfaces was needed.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Thus, JavaScript libraries and JavaScript widget libraries were developed, allowing for developers to concentrate more upon more distinctive applications of Ajax.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] This has led to other companies and groups, such as Microsoft and Yahoo! developing their own JavaScript-based user interface libraries, which find their way into the web applications developed by these companies.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries allow for easier integration of JavaScript with other web development technologies, such as CSS, PHP, Ruby, and Java, while others provide utilities, often in the form of JavaScript functions, to make repetitive and complex tasks less taxing.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Many libraries include code to detect differences between runtime environments and remove the need for applications to allow for such inconsistencies.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Almost all JavaScript libraries are released under either a permissive or copyleft license to ensure license-free distribution, usage, and modification.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries, such as Angular, are classified as frameworks since they exhibit full-stack capabilities and properties not found in general JavaScript libraries.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] All npm packages are JavaScript libraries, but not all libraries are packages.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] Npm serves as a package manager for packages used in Node.js runtimes.
[src:storybook/javascript-library] However, some npm packages offer CDN support for use of the library in both Node.js runtimes as well as the browser.
[src:storybook/page] Storybook is a frontend workshop for building UI components and pages in isolation.
[src:storybook/page] It helps you develop and share hard-to-reach states and edge cases without needing to run your whole app.
[src:storybook/page] Thousands of teams use it for UI development, testing, and documentation.
[src:storybook/page] Ask your AI agent to set up Storybook for you.
[src:storybook/page] Want to know more about installing Storybook?
[src:storybook/page] Storybook includes an active community that supports additional frameworks and libraries.
[src:storybook/page] These community-maintained frameworks are actively developed and maintained by community contributors.
[src:storybook/page] Storybook is a powerful tool that can help you with many aspects of your UI development workflow.
[src:storybook/page] Here are some of the main concepts to get you started.
[src:storybook/page] A story captures the rendered state of a UI component.
[src:storybook/page] Each component can have multiple stories, where each story describes a different component state.
[src:storybook/page] Storybook can analyze your components to automatically create documentation alongside your stories.
[src:storybook/page] This automatic documentation makes it easier for you to create UI library usage guidelines, design system sites, and more.
[src:storybook/page] Stories are a pragmatic starting point for your UI testing strategy.
[src:storybook/page] You already write stories as a natural part of UI development, so testing those stories is a low-effort way to prevent UI bugs over time.
[src:storybook/page] Publishing your Storybook allows you to share your work with others.
[src:storybook/page] You can also embed your stories in places like Notion or Figma.
[src:storybook/page] Once you've learned the basics, explore these other ways to get the most out of Storybook.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] It's an object with annotations that describe the component's behavior and appearance given a set of arguments.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Storybook uses the generic term arguments (args for short) when talking about React’s `props`, Vue’s `props`, Angular’s `@Input`, and other similar concepts.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] A component’s stories are defined in a story file that lives alongside the component file.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] The story file is for development-only, and it won't be included in your production bundle.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] We define stories according to the Component Story Format (CSF), an ES6 module-based standard that is easy to write and portable between tools.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] The key ingredients are the meta (or default export) that describes the component, and named exports that describe the stories.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] The *default* export metadata controls how Storybook lists your stories and provides information used by addons.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Starting with Storybook version 7.0, story titles are analyzed statically as part of the build process.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] The *default* export must contain a `title` property that can be read statically or a `component` property from which an automatic title can be computed.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Using the `id` property to customize your story URL must also be statically readable.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Use the *named* exports of a CSF file to define your component’s stories.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] We recommend you use UpperCamelCase for your story exports.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Here’s how to render `Button` in the “primary” state and export a story called `Primary`.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] By default, stories will render the component defined in the meta (or default export), with the `args` passed to it.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] If you need to render something else, you can provide a function to the `render` property that returns the desired output.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Note how the `render` function spreads `args` onto the Button component.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] This ensures that features like Controls will work as expected, allowing you to dynamically change the Button's properties in the Storybook UI.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Whatever you define at the meta level can be overridden at the story level, so you can still customize the rendering of individual stories if needed.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Finally, `render` functions receive a second `context` argument, which contains all other details for the story, including `parameters`, `globals`, and more.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] React Hooks are convenient helper methods to create components using a more streamlined approach.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] You can use them while creating your component's stories if you need them, although you should treat them as an advanced use case.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] We **recommend** args as much as possible when writing your own stories.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] By default, Storybook uses the name of the story export as the basis for the story name.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] However, you can customize the name of your story by adding a `name` property to the story object.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] This is useful when you want to provide a more descriptive or user-friendly name for your story.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Your story will now be shown in the sidebar with the given text.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] A story is an object that describes how to render a component.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] You can have multiple stories per component, and those stories can build upon one another.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] For example, we can add Secondary and Tertiary stories based on our Primary story from above.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] What’s more, you can import `args` to reuse when writing stories for other components, and it's helpful when you’re building composite components.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] For example, if we make a `ButtonGroup` story, we might remix two stories from its child component `Button`.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] When Button’s signature changes, you only need to change Button’s stories to reflect the new schema, and ButtonGroup’s stories will automatically be updated.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] This pattern allows you to reuse your data definitions across the component hierarchy, making your stories more maintainable.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Each of the args from the story function are live editable using Storybook’s Controls panel.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] It means your team can dynamically change components in Storybook to stress test and find edge cases.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] You can also use the Controls panel to edit or save a new story after adjusting its control values.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] For instance, Actions auto-detects which args are callbacks and appends a logging function to them.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] That way, interactions (like clicks) get logged in the actions panel.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Storybook's `play` function is a convenient helper methods to test component scenarios that otherwise require user intervention.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] They're small code snippets that execute once your story renders.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] You can interact with and debug your story's play function in the interactions panel.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Parameters are Storybook’s method of defining static metadata for stories.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] A story’s parameters can be used to provide configuration to various addons at the level of a story or group of stories.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] For instance, suppose you wanted to test your Button component against a different set of backgrounds than the other components in your app.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] This parameter would instruct the backgrounds feature to reconfigure itself whenever a Button story is selected.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Most features and addons are configured via a parameter-based API and can be influenced at a global, component, and story level.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Decorators are a mechanism to wrap a component in arbitrary markup when rendering a story.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Components are often created with assumptions about ‘where’ they render.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Your styles might expect a theme or layout wrapper, or your UI might expect specific context or data providers.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] A simple example is adding padding to a component’s stories.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Decorators can be more complex and are often provided by addons.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] You can also configure decorators at the story, component and global level.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Sometimes you may have two or more components created to work together.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] For instance, if you have a parent `List` component, it may require child `ListItem` components.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] In such cases, it makes sense to customize the rendering to output the `List` component with different numbers of `ListItem` children.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] You can also reuse *story data* from the child `ListItem` in your `List` component.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] That’s easier to maintain because you don’t have to update it in multiple places.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] Note that there are disadvantages in writing stories like this as you cannot take full advantage of the args mechanism and composing args as you build even more complex composite components.
[src:storybook/writing-stories] For more discussion, see the multi component stories workflow documentation.
